            <div class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What is DNA ligation?</h2>
              <p>
                DNA ligation is the enzymatic process of joining two DNA
                fragments by forming phosphodiester bonds between adjacent
                nucleotides. In molecular cloning, a DNA ligase (most commonly
                T4 DNA ligase) is used to join a linearized plasmid vector with
                one or more insert fragments that have compatible ends.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on
                <strong>molar ratio–based ligation setup</strong>, helping you
                quickly determine how much insert and vector DNA to combine for
                efficient cloning reactions.
              </p>

              <h2>How the ligation calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                The key idea is that ligation efficiency depends on the
                <strong>molar ratio</strong> of insert to vector, not just their
                masses. The calculator converts your DNA masses and sizes into
                moles, applies the desired ratio, and then converts back to
                masses and volumes using your measured concentrations.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Converting DNA mass to moles</h3>
              <p>
                For double-stranded DNA, the approximate molecular weight is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  MW (g/mol) ≈ <strong>bp length × 660 g/mol per bp</strong>
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Given a DNA mass \( m \) in ng and length \( L \) in bp, the
                number of moles \( n \) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ n = \frac{m \times 10^{-9}\ \text{g}}{L \times 660\
                  \text{g/mol}} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Applying the insert:vector molar ratio</h3>
              <p>
                If you choose a vector mass \( m_v \) and an insert:vector molar
                ratio \( R \) (e.g., 3:1), the calculator:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Computes vector moles \( n_v \) from \( m_v \) and vector
                  length.
                </li>
                <li>Sets insert moles \( n_i = R \times n_v \).</li>
                <li>
                  Converts \( n_i \) back to an insert mass \( m_i \) using the
                  insert length.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ m_i = n_i \times L_i \times 660\ \text{g/mol} \times
                  10^{9}\ \text{ng/g} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. From mass to volume</h3>
              <p>
                Using your DNA concentrations \( C_v \) and \( C_i \) (ng/µL),
                the pipetting volumes are:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ V_v = \frac{m_v}{C_v}, \quad V_i = \frac{m_i}{C_i} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator then subtracts these DNA volumes, plus ligase and
                buffer, from the total reaction volume to determine how much
                water to add.
              </p>

              <h2>Recommended ligation conditions</h2>
              <h3>Typical starting conditions</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Vector DNA:</strong> 20–100 ng per 10–20 µL reaction.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Insert:vector ratio (sticky ends):</strong> 3:1 to
                  5:1.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Insert:vector ratio (blunt ends):</strong> 5:1 to
                  10:1.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Buffer:</strong> 1× final concentration (e.g., 2 µL of
                  10× buffer in a 20 µL reaction).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>T4 DNA ligase:</strong> follow the manufacturer’s
                  recommendation (often 0.5–1 µL per 20 µL reaction).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Incubation:</strong> 10–30 min at room temperature for
                  sticky ends; 1–4 h or overnight at 16&nbsp;°C for blunt ends.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Example: 3:1 ligation with 50 ng vector</h3>
              <p>Suppose you have:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Vector: 3,000 bp, 50 ng/µL, using 50 ng.</li>
                <li>Insert: 1,000 bp, 25 ng/µL.</li>
                <li>Desired ratio: 3:1 (insert:vector).</li>
              </ul>
              <p>The calculator will output approximately:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Vector volume ≈ 1.0 µL (50 ng / 50 ng/µL).</li>
                <li>
                  Insert mass ≈ 75 ng (to achieve 3× the moles of vector).
                </li>
                <li>Insert volume ≈ 3.0 µL (75 ng / 25 ng/µL).</li>
                <li>
                  For a 20 µL reaction with 10% 10× buffer and 1 µL ligase:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      2.0 µL 10× buffer, 1.0 µL ligase, 1.0 µL vector, 3.0 µL
                      insert, 13.0 µL water.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Practical tips for successful ligation</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Dephosphorylate the vector</strong> (for sticky-end
                  cloning) to reduce self-ligation background.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use fresh, properly stored ligase buffer</strong>; ATP
                  degradation is a common cause of failed ligations.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Verify DNA quality</strong> by gel electrophoresis;
                  degraded or contaminated DNA ligates poorly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Keep total DNA mass reasonable</strong> (typically
                  &lt; 200–300 ng in a 20 µL reaction) to avoid overly viscous
                  reactions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Include controls:</strong> vector-only (no insert) and
                  insert-only controls help diagnose background and
                  contamination.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>What is a good insert:vector ratio for DNA ligation?</h3>
              <p>
                For sticky-end ligations, 3:1 or 5:1 insert:vector molar ratios
                are common starting points. For blunt-end ligations, 5:1 to 10:1
                is often used. If you see many empty vectors, try increasing the
                insert ratio or decreasing the vector mass.
              </p>

              <h3>How much vector DNA should I use?</h3>
              <p>
                Using 20–100 ng of vector per reaction is typical. Lower amounts
                (e.g., 20–50 ng) can reduce background from self-ligation,
                especially when combined with vector dephosphorylation.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator support multiple inserts?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, but you need to run the calculation separately for each
                insert. Decide on a ratio for each fragment relative to the
                vector, compute the required mass and volume for each, then
                combine all inserts with the vector and ligation mix. Keep the
                total volume and DNA mass within recommended limits.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for Golden Gate or Gibson Assembly?</h3>
              <p>
                The basic molar ratio math still applies, but Golden Gate and
                Gibson protocols often specify their own recommended fragment
                ratios and total DNA amounts. You can use this calculator to
                estimate fragment volumes, then adapt them to your specific
                protocol.
              </p>
